Question 2

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Basics of Lexical Analysis

#include <stdio.h>


int main()

{

    int 1a,sum#;

    a=+2;

    a+=3;

    b=1;

    sum=+a+b;

   

    printf("sum is %d\n",sum;


    return 0;

}

Select the correct option.


It has two lexical errors, one syntax error, one semantic error.

Correct answer

It has two lexical errors, two syntax errors, one semantic error.

It has two lexical errors, three syntax errors, one semantic error.

It has one lexical error, three syntax errors, one semantic error.

Solution

Hide

Lexical error occurs when compiler does not recognize a sequence of characters as lexical token.

Therefore, 1a and sum# , these are two lexical errors, as any variable cannot begin with digit and can not have special symbol (such as #)



Syntax error is occurred when syntax of code is wrong.

Therefore,  printf("sum is %d\n",sum;

In the above statement closing parenthesis is missing which is a syntax error.



Semantic error occurs when there is type-conversion,type-checking,declaration of variable.

Therefore, Variable “b” is not declared which is a semantic error.

Assume the given regular expression is used for tokenization by longest matching prefix rule then String “babaaabbaababbb” will be tokenized into ____ tokens. (Longest matching prefix rule means the scanning begins from left and the maximal matching portion is considered as one token).

3

4

Correct answer

5

Tokenization of the given string by the given regular expression is not possible.

Solution

Hide

Given string is "babaaabbaababbb"

Considering left to right :

baba , this is not considerable because given grammar can not generate this.

Therefore we will consider

Token 1: bab.

Similarly, 

Token 2: aaabb 

Token 3: aabab 

Token 4: bb

Answer will be 4.

Question 7

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Introduction of Compiler

Consider the following grammar

S→Sa | bB |ϵ

B→Bb |ϵ

Number of conflicts in LL(1) parsing table are _____


3

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

S-> Sa will go under first(Sa)

When S->ϵ is used first(Sa)=first(ϵa)=a

When S->bB is used first(Sa)=first(bBa)=b

So S->Sa will go under {a,b}

S->bB will go under {b}

S-> ϵ will go under follow(S)

follow(S)= {a, $}

B->Bb will go under first(Bb)=(ϵb)={b}

B->ϵ will go under follow(B)

follow(B)= b // due to B->Bb

follow(B)= follow(S) // due to S->bB 

So follow(B)={a,b,$}

Question 15

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Introduction of Compiler

Consider the given below regular expressions over ∑={0,1}

r1: 0*1*1*

r2: 1*1*0*

The regular expression for L(r1) ∩ L(r2) is:

Φ

{ϵ}

(0*+1*)

Correct answer

None of the above

Solution

Hide

r1: 0*1*1* is equivalent to 0*1*

r2: 1*1*0* is equivalent to 1*0*

The strings in L(r1) ={ϵ, 0, 1, 00, 01, 11, 000, 001,….}

The strings in L(r2) ={ϵ, 1, 0, 11, 00, 10, 111, 000, 110,….}

The strings which is common are { ϵ, 0, 1, 00, 11, 000, 111, ………..}

Hence the regular expression for (L(r1) ∩ L(r2)) is (0*+1*)

Question 17

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Basics of Lexical Analysis

Consider the following C-code:

void main( )

{

int a,b,sum;

sum=a+b;

printf(“Sum =%d \n”, sum);

}

Select the correct statement from the options. [MSQ]

Both printf and sum are lexemes matching with pattern for token id (identifier).

Correct answer

“Sum =%d \n” is a lexeme matching with pattern literal.

Correct answer

void is a lexeme matching with pattern void

Correct answer

comma “,”is not considered as lexeme and deleted by lexical analyser.

Solution

Hide

A token is a pair consisting of a token name and an optional attribute value. A lexeme is a sequence of characters in the source program that matches the pattern for a token and is identified by the lexical analyzer as an instance of that token. 

For example: int value=3; Lexeme is “value” and Token is <id,1>

Types of tokens:

The different Token classes are as follows:﻿

Class 1: One token per keyword. 

Class 2: Tokens for the operators. 

Class 3: One token representing all identifiers 

Class 4: Tokens representing constants (e.g. numbers) 

Class 5: Tokens for punctuation symbols such as left and right parenthesis, comma, semicolon.

So comma is also a lexeme which matches with pattern token class 5.

Consider languages L1 and L2 such that

Select the correct option﻿

L1 U L2= 0*1*2*

L1 ∩ L2 is CFL

L1 U L2 is inherently ambiguous

Correct answer

All of the above

Solution

Hide

which is an inherently ambiguous language.﻿

Suppose Grammar G1 generates L1 and G2 generates L2, then L1 L2 is generated by grammar

G-> G1 | G2

The common strings such as “abc” can be generated by G1 or G2 thus there are always two parse trees for common strings and hence the language is inherently ambiguous.

L1 ∩ L2 is CSL.

Introduction of Compiler

Let G1 and G2 be two CFG over Σ = {0, 1}, such that

G1:           X → 0X1 | XX | ϵ

G2:           X→ 0X1X | 0X1 | 01X | 01

Select the correct option.


Both G1 and G2 derive the same language.

G1 is unambiguous while G2 is ambiguous

Correct answer

G1 is LL(1) while G2 is not LL(1)

Both G1 and G2 are not LL(1)

Solution

Hide

G1 derives string “ϵ” while G2 doesn’t, so both are not deriving the same language. G1 is unambiguous while G2 is ambiguous. Both G1 and G2 are not LL(1) grammar, as G1 is ambiguous as well as it has left recursion, whereas G2 has left factoring.

Question 24

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Bottom Up/Shift Reduce Parser

Consider the following options and select the correct one. [MSQ]

Every CLR(1) grammar is unambiguous.

Correct answer

Every unambiguous grammar is CLR(1).

Every DCFL has a CFG which is CLR(1).

Correct answer

Every regular grammar is CLR(1).

Solution

Hide

Every CLR(1) grammar must be unambiguous but every unambiguous grammar need not be LR(1). For example the grammar

S-> aSa | bSb | ϵ is unambiguous but it is not CLR(1).

Every DCFL has a CFG which is CLR(1). Every regular grammar need not be CLR(1) as a regular grammar can be ambiguous also. For ex:

S-> aS | a | ϵ is an ambiguous grammar as for string “a” there are two parse trees.

Tree 1: S->aS -> a

Tree 2: S->a

Question 29

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Basics of Run Time Environment

Consider the following options and select the correct one. [MSQ]

A basic block is a sequence of instructions where control enters the sequence at the beginning and exits at the end.

Correct answer

Directed acyclic graph can be used for common subexpression elimination.

Correct answer

Live variable analysis can be used for dead code elimination.

Correct answer

x=20*22 => x=42 is an example of common subexpression elimination.

Solution

Hide

x=20*22 => x=42 is an example of common subexpression elimination is a false statement.

 

 Common subexpression elimination (CSE) is a compiler optimization that searches for instances of identical expressions (i.e., they all evaluate to the same value), and analyzes whether it is worthwhile replacing them with a single variable holding the computed value.

For ex: Consider the following code:

m=y+z * p

n= y+z *k

The common subexpression is “y+z” we can be calculate it one time and replace in both expression

temp=y+z

m= temp*p

n= temp*k

Question 31

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Basics of Run Time Environment

Consider the following ANSI C code segment:

z = x + 3 + y+2;

for (i = 0; i < 200; i++) {

   if (z > i)

   {

          p = p + x + 3 + y + 2;

   } 

else

  {

          q = q + x + 3 + y + 2;

   }

  i++;

  }

 

Assume common subexpression elimination is applied on the code. The number of addition in the optimized code is ______


203

103

Correct answer

102

101

Solution

Hide

Here, x+3 + y+2 is a common subexpression.

The code after common subexpression elimination will be

 

z = x + 3 + y + 2;

for (i = 0; i < 200; i ++) {

   if (z > i)

   {

          p = p + z;

   } 

else

  {

          q = q + z;

   }

    i++;

  }

Loop will execute 100 times (as two times i++), so 100 additions will be inside the loop. Outside loop 3 additions, hence total 103 additions.


Question 32

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Activation Record

Consider the following code segment.

d=a - g;

e=d * b;

d=e + c;

e=g - f;

e=d * e;



The minimum number of total variables required to convert the above code segment to static assignment form is ______

10

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

In Static Single Assignment form(SSA) each assignment to a variable should be specified with distinct names. Generally, subscripts are used to distinguish each definition of variables.


In the given code segment, there are two assignments of the variable d


d=a-g;

d=e + c;


and three assignments of the variable e.


e=d * b;

e=g - f;

e=d * e;


Hence two variables viz d1, d2 should be used for specifying distinct assignments of d and for e it is renamed as e1, e2 and e3 for each assignment of e. Hence, total number of variables is 10 (d1, d2, e1, e2, e3, a, b, c, f, g). and there are 5 temporary variables.

Static Single Assignment form(SSA) of the given code segment is:


d1=a - g;

e1=d1 * b;

d2=e1 + c;

e2=g - f;

e3=d2 * e2;
